  <data name="FullDescription" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>A process that receives a data flow crossing a trust boundary is accepting input from a less trusted zone. If it does not sanitize or validate that input, an attacker can carry injection or tampering payloads (SQL, command, or script injection) into the more trusted zone.

This rule is violated for any process whose SanitizesInput property is No or unset and that has an inbound edge crossing a trust boundary.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="HelpText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Validate and sanitize all input the process accepts from across the trust boundary (allow-list validation, parameterized queries, output encoding for downstream sinks), then set its SanitizesInput property to Yes.

If the inbound flow does not actually cross a trust boundary, correct the placement of the trust boundary or the edge so the diagram reflects reality.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="MessageText" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Process [{0}] receives input across a trust boundary but does not sanitize it, allowing injection or tampering.</value>
